in-and-the-decision-boundary-is-load-voltage-plus-gpio-voltage","target":"transistor-selection-trades-voltage-ceiling-for-gain-and-the-decision-boundary-is-load-voltage-plus-gpio-voltage","line":54},{"title":"pn2222a-npn-transistor-40v-600ma-general-purpose-to92","target":"pn2222a-npn-transistor-40v-600ma-general-purpose-to92","line":60},{"title":"bjt-saturation-requires-base-current-above-collector-current-divided-by-minimum-hfe-making-base-resistor-calculation-a-forced-gain-problem","target":"bjt-saturation-requires-base-current-above-collector-current-divided-by-minimum-hfe-making-base-resistor-calculation-a-forced-gain-problem","line":63},{"title":"wireless-modules-are-overwhelmingly-3v3-making-level-shifting-the-default","target":"wireless-modules-are-overwhelmingly-3v3-making-level-shifting-the-default","line":64},{"title":"passives","target":"passives","line":67},{"title":"eda-fundamentals","target":"eda-fundamentals","line":68}],"metadata":{"description":"At 3.3V GPIO, Vbe=0.7V consumes 21% of the supply leaving only 2.6V across the base resistor -- versus 4.3V at 5V GPIO (14% loss) -- this reduced headroom constrains the base resistor to lower values (2.2K-3.3K) and shrinks the saturation overdrive margin","type":"knowledge-note","source":"docs/parts/pn2222a-npn-transistor-40v-600ma-general-purpose-to92.md","topics":["[[passives]]","[[eda-fundamentals]]"],"confidence":"high","verified":false},"task_lines":[],"tasks":{},"codeblock_ranges":[[16,18]],"key":"knowledge/3v3-gpio-driving-a-bjt-base-loses-21-percent-of-supply-voltage-to-vbe-leaving-less-headroom-for-the-base-resistor.md"},
